    "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
    "body": "Hi @Kikobeats \r\n\r\nFor your first issue, I noticed that you didn't update the slider when new props are given by InstantSearch. Adding something like this should do the trick:\r\n\r\n```js\r\n  componentWillReceiveProps(sliderState) {\r\n    const value = {\r\n      min: sliderState.currentRefinement.min,\r\n      max: sliderState.currentRefinement.max\r\n    }\r\n\r\n    this.setState({\r\n      min: sliderState.min,\r\n      max: sliderState.max,\r\n      value: value\r\n    })\r\n  },\r\n```\r\n\r\nYou might also need this condition around the refine function:\r\n\r\n```js\r\n    if (this.props.currentRefinement.min !== sliderState.values[0] || this.props.currentRefinement.max !== sliderState.values[1]) {\r\n```\r\n\r\nFor the second part, I'm sorry but can you also make a gif of the behavior that's bothering you, I have trouble to understand it correctly. \r\n\r\nFinally, when launching your application I noticed that sometimes, you can end-up with an infinite loop. The reason behind it is the usage of rheostat as a slider. When passing an equal min and max to rheostat, you got 'NaN' from it, and then `react-instantsearch` goes crazy. \r\n\r\nWe will improve the behavior of `react-instantsearch` to avoid the infinite loop and I will open an issue on the rheostat side. \r\n\r\nIn the meantime, if you want to fix this on your side, you can check for the current slider values and don't do a refine if those are `NaN`. \r\n\r\n",
